column169: The freight was shipped to A. Duie Pyle on poor quality pallets.  The pallet had a nail protruding from it resulting in the unintentional release of 1 liter of corrosive liquid. column170: Ensure the shipper is using good quality pallets that are free of protruding nails that damage freight.  According to our dock supervisor, this is becoming a common issue with chem aqua pallets.

column169: ABF stated that while unloading the commodity they noticed the leaking commodity. ABF stated that it appears to have been forklift while being loaded at is previous location. A crew from TLE arrived on-site. Following a site assessment, TLE personnel noted two (2) pounds of sodium hydroxide was rele ased to the pallet and the concrete surfaces of the loading dock. TLE personnel overpacked the one (1) damaged 500-pound supersack of sodium hydroxide into one (1) 95-gallon overpack as hazardous waste. TLE personnel utilized one (1) HEPA vacuum to collect the released sodium hydroxide from the impa cted surfaces. TLE personnel cut up the impacted pallet as waste. All sodium hydroxide impacted material was collected in one (1) 95-gallon overpack as hazardous waste and staged on-site for further management. TLE personnel noted no further acitons required on-site and crews demobilized.

column169: At 0900et the driver was performing a walk around of his equipment and noticed that there were some liquid dripping from the trailer onto the pavement. The driver put down some absorbent and then called our emergency response number. The response team was dispatched and showed up on site at 1045et. The team assessed the situation and began gaining access to the container that was leaking. The container was found and was repacked. The container had a small pinhole in it and only 1-2gallons was released. The team then did a final cleanup with absorbents and were collected and placed in the appropriate containers for proper disposal. The clean up was completed at 1300et.

column169: A Veolia employee was unloading a truck from a pick up of waste material from a customer on the previous day when he noticed liquid under a pallet. The drum was inspected and did not show any signs of leaking. The pallet containing the drum was moved off the truck. While moving the drum, it was noticed that a small amount of liquid was dripping from under the closure ring. The drum's ring was missing the closure nut and the closure ring's gasket was compromised.
column170: Veolia employees were reminded to visually inspect drums in preparation for shipment. The closures and integrity of the containers need to be verified as acceptable prior to transportation. Any container exhibiting questionable integrity must not be utilized for shipping hazardous materials. A container's structural integrity and proper closing are fundamental prerequisites for shipping. Comprehensive visual inspections are a mandatory part of the pre-shipment process.

column169: On Wednesday, June 11, 2025, at approximately 1730 hours, a CSXT crew noticed a tank car (UTLX 212517) leaking a liquid substance from the top of the car.  After a call from the CSX Yardmaster at approximately 1733 hours, a Canton employee walked out to inspect the railcar.  It was determined that the leak was coming from the top of the tank car, out of the pressure relief valve, located under the top fitting protection cover.  This leak was due to the car being loaded during the winter months and the product inside the tank expanding due to sunlight warming the side of the tank, causing the contents to expand, thus reducing the available head space in the car.  A Canton Railroad transload employee came out at 1907 hours and pumped 200 gallons out of the car to prevent further dripping out of the safety valve.
column170: Both the shipper and consignee will be notified of the incident and a recommendation will be made to load the railcars, leaving more head room in the tank for expansion of the product during warm weather months.

column169: Incident Report: Transportation Package Failure and Release Response Sequence of Events Leading to the Incident: On the morning of June 16, 2025, at 8:26 AM, Driver Carnest Nutall contacted dispatch to report that he had run his truck and trailer off the road and into a ditch at the curve where County Road 174 intersects Bob Wilson Road, while traveling northbound. The unit involved was Truck RC-34 pulling Trailer 107, both loaded with chemical product identified under BOL 1150607. The material being transported was M2Guard-HSR105G, manufactured by Foremark Performance for M2 Chemical. The driver was approximately 15 minutes from the delivery location at the time of the incident. Driver Nutall reported that he was unable to stop the truck and trailer due to apparent brake failure. The posted speed limit for the curve was 15 mph, as confirmed by photographs taken at the scene, which also documented tire marks showing the vehicle sliding off the road and rolling. Actions Taken at the Time of Discovery: The driver immediately notified dispatch and confirmed that he had sustained injuries to his head and lower back, but no other vehicles or individuals were involved. Local law enforcement was notified, and Officer Cliff Lance (Phone: 318-426-499) responded to the scene. The Louisiana State Police accident hotline was contacted at 10:19 AM; the call was taken by Amanda, who provided Incident #2121, which was initially given by Officer Lance. E3 Environmental was contacted to oversee environmental remediation and cleanup. They will be providing a cost estimate and handling hazardous materials containment. Nolan's Towing was notified to upright the truck and trailer and coordinate safe offloading of the contents. A secondary trailer, TX-18, operated by Driver Alan Reeves, was dispatched to receive the chemical transfer from the damaged trailer. Description of Package Failure: • The trailer was fully loaded with 45k of M2Guard-HSR105G at the time of the accident. Due to the trailer rolling into a ditch, there is potential for container displacement or compromise, though a full damage assessment was pending at time of report. While no visible punctures, cracks, or leaks were initially confirmed via driver call, an on-site inspection was ordered noticed some seepage from washout cap on dome lid area. Photographs taken at the scene showed clear evidence of road departure, slide marks, and the overturned position of the truck and trailer. • Any cracked, punctured, or ruptured drums will be identified by E3 Environmental and reported under separate documentation. Estimated Duration of Release: The exact duration of any material release is currently unknown pending E3's assessment. However, based on the time of the call (8:26 AM) and environmental response initiation (around 12:30 PM). Scene secured by law enforcement to prevent unauthorized access or ignition hazards. column169: Unmarked fiberboard box containing a 5gal plastic drum of corrosive liquid degreaser. Exterior box has no diamonds, orientation arrows, or OP-900. Package was initially flagged for the corroded external box while unloading a trailer. Hazmat was confirmed via litmus paper testing, and exact material was identified by product label on the side of the drum. The head of the drum appears to have been fitted incorrectly, as there is a gap on one side, allowing contents to spill out. External box appears to have absorbed the majority of the spill but was ruined in the process. No evidence of further spillage was observed.

column169: Hepaco was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 2ft-by-2ft area of the concrete dock floor and estimated that twenty-five (25) gallons of material were released due to a puncture in one (1) 330-gallon poly tote. Hepaco personnel began the tote transfer and transferred eight hundred (800) liters of material. The damaged tote was cut up and placed into poly containers. The contaminated area was decontaminated, neutralized, and cleaned. The generated waste consists of five (5) 55-gallon poly drums containing impacted debris, absorbents, and cut-up tote pieces. All waste was staged onsite at bay 34. The contractor checked out with ESTES terminal employee Shane Smith. The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

column169: On 02/25/2025 at approximately 0645, Dangerous Goods Administration received notification from operations staff at the ramp facility in Greer, SC that the outer packaging of a shipment containing a declared Class 3 dangerous goods commodity was observed to be damp. The shipment consisted of one outer fiberboard box that contained one inner plastic bottle. Initially, the shipment was reported as sustaining outer package damage only with the damp outer packaging believed to result from an unknown external substance.  However, when arranging for final disposition of the package on 6/5/2025, a visible tear in the tape used to secure the top onto the lid observed that had not been previously documented, changing the determination that the initial reported damp outer packaging. may have resulted from a small amount of leakage from the cap inner bottle.

column43: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column169: On June 13, 2025, one (1) 3,000-pound tote of sulfuric acid was damaged by an explosion inside the tote and released approximately two hundred (200) gallons of product to the trailer interior and terminal yard. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from EnviroServe (ES) to remediate the site. ES personnel deployed soda ash to the trailer interior, pavement and tires of nearby trailers. All sulfuric acid impacted material was collected and containerized into fifteen (15) 55-gallon drums and eleven (11) 35-gallon drums for future terminal disposal.

column169: On June 10, 2025, four (4) 1-gallon pails of paint were crushed in transit and released approximately two (2) gallons of product to the trailer floor and adjacent freight. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from American Safety (AS) to remediate the impacted site. Before AS personnel's arrival, onsite employees collected some released material and impacted wood into a trash can. AS personnel utilized absorbent pads to remediate the trailer floor and containerized the waste in one (1) 55-gallon drum. The crew transferred the contents of the trash can in the previously mentioned drum. All impacted pails were containerized in one (1) additional 55-gallon drum.

When driver was done loading and thought he had closed all of his valves one was not closed all the way and when disconnecting the hose material began to come out into the containment pad. The material was all contained in second containment and non was released to the environment. The material was quickly pumped up and placed into drums and absorbents were used to collect the rest of the material and placed into drums to be properly disposed of. The material was cleaned up within an hour time frame.
column170: The driver was new and was not familiar with this facility and will be retrained and it was reinforced with the employee to use stop work authority on tasks that he has not been trained on.

GROUND PACKAGE, FULLY LABELED HAZMAT PACKAGE THAT APPEARED TO BE LEAKING WAS DISCOVERED BY A LOADER ON THE PD2. THE LOADER LEFT THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR. A DMP RESPONDER ARRIVED WITHIN 5 MINUTES DONNING THE APPROPRIATE PPE WITH A FULLY STOCKED SPILLCART. USING THE DECISION TREE AND CORRECT RESPONSE SHEET IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE PACKAGE COULD BE SAFELY TRANSPORTED BACK TO THE DMP. UPON FURTHER INSPECTION IT WAS REVEALED THAT ONE OF THE CAPS ON ONE OF THE INNER ONE GALLON PLASTIC CONTAINERS WAS LOOSE BY 1/2 A TURN AND 6 OUNCES OF LIQUID HAD LEAKED OUT ONTO THE OUTER CARTON.

On June 9, 2025, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN1791 was damaged in a load shift and released approximately fifteen (15) gallons of product to the trailer floor and asphalt beneath the trailer. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Hull's Environmental Services (HES) to remediate the site. The crew containerized the damaged drum in one (1) 95-gallon overpack. HES personnel utilized granular absorbents and hand tools to collect all impacted material into one (1) 55-gallon drum for disposal.

column169: Clean Harbors was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 6ft-by-40ft area of the trailer floor and concrete dock floor and estimated that thirty (30) gallons of material was released due to one (1) 55-gallon metal drum being damaged. Before arrival, the terminal overpacked the damaged drum into one (1) 85-gallon metal drum. Clean Harbors personnel applied absorbents to the affected areas on the trailer and dock. The overpack, impacted absorbents, boom, PPE, pads were all containerized into three (3) 55-gallon metal drums. Clean Harbors personnel staged the waste onsite and received approval from the Dayton Freight Lines manager. The generated waste will remain onsite for the Dayton Freight Lines team to coordinate disposal

On June 3, 2025, one (1) 55-gallon drum of sodium hydroxide solution fell over in transit due to improper securement and released approximately four (4) ounces of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Environmental Restoration (ER) to remediate the impacted site. The crew utilized absorbent pads and cleaning agents to wipe down the drum and impacted floor. ER personnel then replaced the bung on the drum and staged it onsite for further processing. All impacted materials were containerized in one (1) 5-gallon pail for future disposal.

column43: LITHIUM ION BATTERIES INCLUDING LITHIUM ION POLYMER BATTERIES
column169: On 06/09/2025 at approximately 2055, Dangerous Goods Administration received notification of a lithium battery fire.  The shipment consisted of one fiberboard box that appeared to contain 2 lithium batteries.  During sort operations, the shipment began to smoke.  The package was extinguished and submerged in water to neutralize the heat.  Further investigation revealed that the battery shipment was not prepared in accordance with IATA regulations, missing the required markings, labeling, packaging and paperwork, deeming it undeclared dangerous goods.  The package is being held, pending an investigation by the FAA.

column169: On June 2, 2025, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN2922 was punctured in transit and released approximately five (5) gallons of product to the trailer interior and pavement beneath. column169: While offloading a truck at Veolia's 10 day intransit facility in Dayton, OH, a Veolia employee noticed a small spot on the truck bed. Upon further inspection, the employee discovered a drum that had two small pin holes approximately a 1/3 of the way down the drum. The drum was immediately overpacked and the small spill was cleaned up.
column170: Veolia employees were reminded to visually inspect all drums in preparation for transportation. The integrity of the containers need to be verified and acceptable for for shipment. Any container exhibiting questionable integrity must not be utilized for shipping hazardous materials. A container's structural integrity and proper sealing are fundamental prerequisites for shipping. Comprehensive visual inspections are a mandatory part of the pre-shipment process. Containers not meeting these requirements shall be overpacked, or not accepted for shipment.

The shipment consisted of 3 different containers containing paint and one container holding a corrosive substance.  The package showed signs of spillage on the outside.  Further inspection revealed that one of the paint containers leaked inside of the package, resulting in spillage onto the other containers in the package.  The shipment was not prepared in accordance with IATA regulations, missing the required markings, labeling, packaging and paperwork.  The package is being held, pending an investigation by the FAA.

During sort operations at the SEAR location A fiberboard box was discovered with signs of a release. While investigating the shipment the spill agent observed two plastic bottles inside that had warning stickers. After obtaining the SDS the contents were a class 8 UN3264. The outer fiberboard box didn't have any DG markings or paperwork required for transport. All contents were placed into a steel salvage package and is being held at the location for the FAA.

The shipper advised the cargo was non-haz lead cans. Because its overpack crate broke in the ocean container from China to the U.S., our Chicago CFS discovered a package with a class 7 label and UN3332 markings. After speaking to the consignee we learned this classification was incorrect. The package was now classified as EMPTY and was UN2908. It was being returned to them because they are the manufacturer. They advised us how to correctly label and mark the package before they had it picked up.
column170: We advised our Shanghai office to watch for future shipments from this shipper or future shipments to the same consignee as it most likely will be radioactive. Vanguard Logistics Services prohibits all class 7 shipments.

column169: On June 11, 2025, one (1) 5-gallon pail of paint was crushed by a loading strap during transit and released approximately one (1) gallon of product to the dock floor, pallet, and surrounding freight. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from EnviroServe (ES) to remediate the site. The crew utilized absorbent pads and cleaning agents to remediate the impacted areas. All impacted materials and the damaged pail were containerized in one (1) 55-gallon drum for disposal.

During sort operations at the MEMH location a fiberboard box was discovered with signs of a release. Inside of the fiberboard box were four metal cans with screw caps in a plastic bag. The cap on one can wasn't sealed causing the release. All contents were placed into a steel salvage package and a new declaration will be obtained for movement.

column169: Pkg is considered Undeclared as it is missing required Hazmat markings for shipment containing aerosols. Contents of original pkg repacked in FedEx repack box. Pkg was damaged at the origin terminal and Damaged Package Report (DPR) was filed. Required accompanying documents were not filed. Shipment "Service Code" designates Ltd Qty. Damaged portion (presumably non-hazardous cleaner) was removed from the original packaging and discarded. Remaining contents: laundry detergent, water filtration pitcher and sunscreen (aerosol) were repacked in the oversized FedEx carton with no packing material. Vent cap came off laundry detergent bottle allowing liquid to leak wetting and coating contents. Removal of pkg from sortation and inspection resulted in the discovery of the undeclared aerosol contents.

column169: attachment Name:DPR by Tracking ID (PDF Version)(FY24) (6).pdf

Upon opening the trailer at the disposal facility, it was discovered that part of the load had shifted during transportation. Thirty 5-gallon pails containing lithium scrap soaked in mineral oil had shifted off the pallet and fell over in the nose of the trailer. One of the lids on a 5-gallon pail had loosened up as a result of the load shifting and began to leak. Approximately 0.25 gallons of material was spilled. The spill was contained and cleaned up appropriately. The material was then incinerated later the same day.
column170: A corrective actions meeting was scheduled immediately following the report of the leak to discuss the incident and the corrective measures to be taken to prevent a reoccurrence. In the future, pails should not be double stacked when not banded to the pallet. Containers must be shrink-wrapped to the pallet (properly secured), as well as inspecting containers prior to shipment to ensure all lids are securely on.

column169: On June 12, 2025, at 1542 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar Inway personnel in Princeton, IL regarding the release of TRANSCHEM Muriatic Acid. Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of 1.0 gallon of TRANSCHEM Muriatic Acid (UN1789, 8, II) from (1) 1-gallon plastic jug onto the trailer floor. The release was reportedly due to a load shift causing the jug to be smashed, impacting the trailer floor and 23 cardboard boxes containing (92) 1-gallon jugs of product. The release was cleaned with absorbent pads and the proper PPE. No drains or waterways were impacted by the release. All jugs of product within the impacted cardboard boxes were removed from the boxes and containerized along with the damaged cardboard. All waste generated from addressing this release was containerized in (4) 55-gallon DFs which were taken off-site by the contractor for proper disposal.
